annotation.TEXT: Almost, but Lance does a mid-turn heal with a Hyper Potion. Certainly much better than a Super Potion, but at these high levels, it's not enough to fully heal Moltres, and another Surf should still take it down.
Next up is Hitmonlee, which Keeper should also be able to easily destroy with Psychic.

Aw, that's right. I left my fishing rods in the PC for this E4 run. But, as you can see, I've stocked up on 25 each of most healing items, and I'm also carrying every Ether and Elixir I have, just in case.
Yeah, if Dragonite somehow lives and it knows Thunderbolt or Thunder, I'd rather take only 2x damage instead of 4x (if I went with Radical).

BTW, my Cut user during the game was the Dux (Farfetch'd) that you can trade a Spearow for in Vermilion City. I kind of didn't want to trade the Spearow that I happened to catch on Route 5, but no one else I had at the time could use Cut, except for my starter, and I definitely didn't want to ruin Flame Hyenard's moveset with that awful HM move.
E4 KOs: 5
And so, Lorelei is defeated! That went very well!
Ha. I barely felt that. Radical, finish it off with Strength!
Muk? That's not a Gengar! Also, it's level 96. However, it is still a poison-type, so it's Earthquake time!
Or, you can stop watching the video now if you want (like if you've already seen these credits something like 151 times already).
And that's it for Agatha.
Beedrill? Wow, that's different and unexpected. Okay, I think it's finally time to give Flame Hyenard a turn!
And Beedrill has been totally burninated.

Seaking? That's unexpected. Well, I think the only thing I'd really have to worry about is Horn Drill, and that's only if I'm slower than it, and I'm pretty sure most (if not all) of my guys are faster. (In Gen. 1, OHKO moves only have a chance of working if the user outspeeds the target.)

I decided to go with Lord Helix, who resists ice, and has a really high Special stat, so even Psychic moves shouldn't hurt too much. (Too bad Omastar can't learn Rock Slide for whatever dumb reason in Gen. 1...)
Hmm... This is probably overkill, but whatever.
Yeah, looks like Flamethrower was stronger anyway. Probably because Pidgeot's Special is lower than its Defense. I guess I'll finish it off with Swift.
BURN! BURN TO THE GROUND! BURN! WOO! BURN TO THE GROUND!
Lord Helix was really nice to have on my team, because it let me fight against exploding Pokémon without fear.
Good thing this isn't Gen. 6, where Dragonite could have Multiscale to survive such a hit, and also be equipped with a Weakness Policy, which would allow it to utterly wreck me in retaliation!
Nope! A powerful STAB Earthquake from The Fonz still one-shots it!
Cloyster's next. Also, no surprise there. Its Special stat isn't so great, so I think Battery Jay can one-shot it with its Thunderbolt.
Okay, I'll go with Radical. Thunderbolt will probably 2HKO, and I might have to eat an Ice Beam in the process, but I'm sure Radical can take it.

I got another crit there, but it wasn't quite enough. However, Zapdos used Agility again, so I can finish it off unscathed. Hmm... Did it even have Drill Peck? Or was the AI screwed up by the fact that I had a poison-type in play (just like how Venomoth beat a Dragonite in TPP)?
Wow, that didn't quite do it? Yeah, unfortunately, Charizard's Special, while still decent, is lower than I'd like it to have been. At least Agatha wasted her turn on a meaningless Super Potion.
E4 KOs: 4

Finally, there's a Pokémon that Agatha used in the original game! I think I'll let Flame Hyenard take a shot at it with his Dig move. (In Gen. 1, Dig is just as powerful as Earthquake, with 100 power. In Gens. 2 & 3, it was nerfed to a lame 60 power, then got a bit better with 80 power in Gen. 4.)
Alright, it's final boss time!
Wow, I seriously wasn't expecting the Elite 4 and Champion to all be this easy. Maybe I should've stopped grinding at level 90, or even earlier...
Oh, heck, yeah! Critical hit, baby!

Rage does boost the user's Attack stat as the user takes hits, but even at maximum Attack, Rage would only be about as powerful as an unboosted Strength (80 power), so why not just use Strength or a similarly strong move instead to begin with?
And down it goes! Alright!
Surf's up, Jynx! It probably won't OHKO, but getting a 2HKO should be easy enough.
And lastly, we have his usual closer, Machamp, who is at level 97 here. Hey, Keeper, want to finish your sweep?
I could easily wreck this thing with Battery Jay, but I want Radical to do the job, since Battery Jay already wrecked two of Gary's other Pokémon.

Whoa, sweet! A critical hit! Nice job, Lord Helix! (Critical hit odds depend on the base speed stat of the user in Gen. 1, and Lord Helix is one of my slower Pokémon, making it less likely for him to get crits than most of the rest of my team.)
Radical probably could've handled it just as well, but whatever.
Yep, and it's the Gyarados that I thought it would be. Here, have a Thunderbolt, courtesy of Battery Jay.
Can't go back now. (Well, you can with a glitch, which lets you return to Agatha's room, but that doesn't accomplish anything meaningful.)
Once again, no healing needs to be done. However, I am gonna switch Battery Jay to the front, just in case Lance still opens with Gyarados.
Or, I could switch to get rid of the confusion, but... I think I'll take a chance here.
Oh, cool. Everyone scored either 4 or 5 KOs each, so that means I used everybody about evenly.

(I forget if you can actually catch anything here, but if I still had the Super Rod in my inventory, I certainly would've tried, and it would've counted as my Indigo Plateau encounter, assuming it wasn't a duplicate, since I did use the "dupes clause" during this run.)

I'm trying to decide who to lead with here, since Gary could have almost anything. He'll probably just open with that Pidgeot that I've seen him begin with before, but since Lance had the three legendary birds, who knows? Gary could be packing Mewtwo and/or Mew for all I know.
I was thinking about using Lord Helix there instead, but I decided on Battery Jay.
Wing Attack, eh? Unfortunately for you, Wing Attack's power is only a weak 35 (same as Tackle) in Gen. 1. Now, I wonder if Flamethrower would be more powerful than that critical Slash...
And let's watch the credits roll!

So, what should I do? Hmm... I could switch to Keeper or Battery Jay right now, but I think I'll let The Fonz handle this. The Fonz resists fighting moves, and I don't think Primeape can learn Earthquake...

Uh, oh. Tauros. Yes, it's another normal-type, but Tauros is pretty powerful, so that scares me. I could go with Lord Helix to resist its normal-type moves, but what if it knows Earthquake, Horn Drill, or Fissure?
Yeah, Gyarados isn't getting up from that.
Alright, deep breath, and... Let's do this!

And lastly, we have Lapras. Nothing surprising about that (so the only change to Lorelei in this hack, besides levels, was swapping out her Slowbro for Seaking). Now, Lapras is pretty defensive, so I'll probably need to endure at least one hit. I'll use Radical, who isn't weak to ice.
Nuts.
Oh, man. Not even 50% damage, but it's wasting a turn on Acid Armor, which is useless against my special attacks.

Parasect in Gen. 1 has three x4 weaknesses: Poison (no longer the case starting in Gen. 2), flying, and fire! Now, Charizard can't learn any offensive poison moves, and it can't learn Fly in Red and Blue (it can in Yellow, though), so that just leaves one option...
Oh, man. I just thought of something. What if Lorelei's Lapras knew Thunderbolt? That would've been bad for Radical! (Fortunately, it didn't, or at least it didn't use it.)
BURN! BURN TO THE GROUND! BURN! WOO! BURN TO THE GROUND! TRI-FORMATION! (If Charizard could learn Tri-Attack, I so would've taught it to my Flame Hyenard instead of Swift!)
LOL, another critical hit that I probably didn't need.
Oh, and this Lapras is level 96 (the rest of her team were level 94). Now, I'm hoping Thunderbolt will at least 2HKO, or maybe I'll get lucky and land another crit...
So, Kingler is next. Well, at least it's not another bird. Now, it could have Guillotine, but that would only be a threat if my guys were slower, and my guys are most definitely not slower!
No, Lance, I don't think my league challenge is ready to end quite yet!
Yep, it's level 99, but Lord Helix outspeeds it anyway. Will this Ice Beam be enough? It should be, I would think...

Alright, so Lorelei's opening with Dewgong, which isn't surprising, since that's what she normally opens with in the original game. However, this one's level 94 (I was expecting the E4+Champion to use level 95-100 duders, so my prediction was close). Radical, give it a Thunderbolt!

I also have a level 95 Pidgeot named Abba Jesus in the PC, who is my Fly user, but unfortunately, I can only bring six Pokémon with me, so it was eventually decided that Pidgeot would be the benched one. Sorry, Abba Jesus, but I still consider you a valued member of my team!
And here's one more look at my amazing team! You guys are awesome!

Ha! I'm not using special attacks right now, so your Light Screen is useless! (And unlike later games, Light Screen and Reflect only buff the user in Gen. 1, and won't linger around after the user is KO-ed or switches out.)
Lance's last Pokémon is Dragonite, which is probably at level 99. Hmm... I definitely want to bring out an Ice Beam user, so I think I'll go with Lord Helix again.
Well, maybe I can paralyze Zapdos. That would be neat.

So, here's a look at my team that I'm gonna go into the Elite 4 with. I grinded them all to level 95, because I totally expect the Elite 4 to have Pokémon ranging from 95-100, from what I've observed of the level curve so far (Victory Road trainers had Pokémon in the low 90s).

So, there was Flame Hyenard, my starter (and Pallet Town encounter, obviously). And next we have Lord Helix, my Omastar, which I revived from the Helix Fossil ASAP (my Cinnabar Island encounter, of course).
Easy one-shot.
Well, I think I'll go with Lord Helix anyway. What are the odds that Gary was smart enough to teach Tauros those nasty moves?
Poliwrath? Now, there's another surprise. But, it is part fighting-type, so I guess that makes more sense than an Onix! And this also means Keeper should have no problem with it.
Next is Hitmonchan, which isn't a surprise. I think I'll hand this one over to Keeper.
Alright, never mind, because I got a critical hit! Nice!
FLAWLESS VICTORY.
I remember a particularly nasty Tauros in Pokémon Stadium that liked to use Body Slam to paralyze your guys, followed by Horn Drill or Fissure to potentially one-shot them.
I was thinking of switching to Keeper for a moment there, but I trust that The Fonz can get the job done!
Ha! I got through that time!
One pixel away!
Oh, man! It's a Parasect! Flame Hyenard, this one's all yours!
E4 KOs: 4

Leer? Pfft, whatever. And it didn't even work. Yeah, in Gen. 1 (and maybe Gen. 2), for some reason, debuffs that the opponent uses on you will sometimes fail, even if they should have 100% accuracy (and I'm not talking about the 1/256 miss bug that Gen. 1 games have).
And Agatha's last Pokémon is her usual Gengar, which is at level 98 now. I'm pretty sure Dig can one-shot it, since Gengar's Defense isn't very good.
Ha! Even with your +4 Defense, Strength was enough to knock off your last sliver of life! And that's game!
I think Muk is pretty good defensively, but will it survive this Earthquake?

Alright, it's Pidgeot, but it's level 100, not 98! Well, whatever. Two levels shouldn't make much of a difference. Flame Hyenard, use Slash for an automatic critical! (In Gen. 1, moves like Slash had a hugely boosted crit rate, and if the user is even remotely fast, criticals are guaranteed!)

Now here we have Battery Jay, my Zapdos. When I noticed during this game that I was using a lot of the same Pokémon that TPP was using, I decided I wanted to try for Zapdos. Fortunately, he let me catch him without too much of a fight (I think it only took me 4 Ultra Balls).
Okay, looks like Thunderbolt will 2HKO, assuming Radical doesn't slap himself silly in confusion...
Okay, let me think about this for a moment...
E4 KOs: 4
You know what? I think I'll start with my starter, and I'll just switch out to Keeper if he opens with an uber psychic-type. But, if it's Pidgeot, I'll let Flame Hyenard stay in to handle it.
Keeper, use Psychic!
So, I'm sensing a pattern with the E4's levels. Is Lance's opener at 97?

Let's Surf on this bird! ...Wow, I'm surprised I'm faster. Must be all the stat exp. I acquired while grinding. (Stat exp. back in Gens. 1 and 2 is basically like the EVs of Gens. 3 and beyond, though it's calculated a bit differently.)
Oh, man. If I get paralyzed, I want to try something.

Alright, so Jynx is next. This one's tricky. You'd think I could just roast it with Flame Hyenard, but his Special stat actually isn't all that high (so he probably couldn't one-shot Jynx), and he's weak to ice. (Fire doesn't resist ice in Gen. 1.)

Super Potion in the middle of a turn? Lorelei, you cheater! (Yeah, they can do that in Gen. 1 if you outspeed the opponent.) However, the Super Potion heals so little at these high levels, and it used up Lorelei's attack turn, so I get to beat Dewgong without getting hurt!
E4 KOs: 5
Oh, and this is actually a Nuzlocke run that I was doing off to the side just for fun, but I decided I'd record a video of me taking on the Elite 4!
Well, I hope you all enjoyed watching me destroy the Elite 4 in this hack! Smell ya later!
Here's The Fonz, who started off as a male Nidoran that I caught on Route 22 (just west of Viridian City) early in the game. And yes, most of these nicknames are inspired by Twitch Plays Pokémon.
Now, if Gary continues to follow the level pattern that I've seen so far, his first five Pokémon will be at level 98, and his final Pokémon (most likely his starter) will be level 100.
Nuts. No paralysis, and it boosted its speed with Agility, so it's surely faster than me now.
Primeape? I wasn't expecting that. And, it's level 95. (Come to think of it, why doesn't Bruno use a Primeape in the original game?)
Battle start!

Up next is Weezing. Now, The Fonz has also been good at defusing these things before they could blow, so even though Weezing is even more defensive than Muk (I think), it should also go down with one Earthquake! (Good thing there's no Levitate ability to worry about here!)
LOL, pointless critical hit. That's alright, since Lord Helix got a crit at a nice time earlier.
Well, that went perfectly, so I don't have to do any healing! Now, Agatha's next, and I'm expecting her to open with Gengar, so I think I'll leave The Fonz in the front.
Alright, it's time to d-d-d-d... d-d-d-d-duel! (Wait, this isn't Yu-gi-oh! Well, let's duel anyway!)
Oh, so close! ...Fury Attack? Is that the best move you can use against me? ...Well, maybe.

I'm glad Gyarados's Special stat is high in Gen. 1! (The Special stat governs both Sp. Attack and Sp. Defense in Gen.1, but the stat was split in Gen. 2, and Gyarados's Sp. Attack got horribly nerfed.)
Really? Acid Armor again? Okay, I'll humor you and use a physical attack this time.
Umm... Let's see here... Man, I wish Lord Helix could've learned Rock Slide in this game... It would've been perfect for this.
Oh, and I just fought off Lance while Surfing on the base of a statue, which is pretty gnarly.
I was trying to decide if I wanted to use Radical or Battery Jay for a moment there, and I've gone with Radical.

Yep, totally saw Zapdos coming. I'm going to switch in The Fonz, who is immune to electric attacks. This way, I should only have to worry about Drill Peck, and maybe Hyper Beam if Lance taught it to Zapdos.
E4 KOs: 4
Speaking of Earthquake... Take this!
Hello, and welcome to this video that I decided to make of the Elite 4 in this Pokémon Red 151 Complete hack!

By the way, I did indeed use the Missingno. glitch to clone TMs, but I didn't clone anything else. No cloned Master Balls, Rare Candies, Vitamins, or anything like that. So, yeah, I did grind all of my guys up to level 95 through battles only.
Now, I expect Bruno to open with an Onix, and The Fonz knows Surf, and I don't want to keep relying on Radical all the time, so I'm moving The Fonz to the front here.
During a lot of the game, Keeper helped me defuse some enemy Koffings and Weezings before they could blow, and he also helped me defend against enemy Psychic types (such as in Sabrina's gym).

Yep, so Gary's next, of course. Now, I once again wasn't damaged, so I don't need to heal. (I don't think I'm running low on PP for any important moves, but I can always use Ethers/Elixirs during the next battle if I really need to.)
Well, I guess we get to see the ending now. It's the same as always.
LOL, Rage! One of THE WORST moves in Gen. 1, permanently locking the user into a move that starts off at only 20 power.
DOUBLE FLAWLESS.
Next up is Keeper, my Hypno, which I caught as a Drowzee on Route 11 (east of Vermilion City). Of course, unlike in TPP, he remained on my team the whole way and evolved.
And lastly, here's Radical, my Gyarados, who began as a Magikarp that I purchased for 500 Pokébucks from the salesman in the Route 4 Pokémon Center next to Mt. Moon. Totally a worthwhile purchase!
Whoa, whoa, whoa! Articuno?! Lance is using the legendary birds?!

So, who should I use? The Fonz and Flame Hyenard are weak to water, and Lord Helix and Keeper are my slowest dudes, and I don't want to risk their heads... So, it'll be either Radical or Battery Jay... Whoops! Hit B by accident while thinking there. Well, Battery Jay it is!

Darn, not quite enough. Oh, but it's wasting its turn on Focus Energy! Ha! Even if Focus Energy did work correctly here (it actually reduces the user's crit rate in Red/Blue/Yellow due to a glitch), he won't have a chance to make use of it!
Huh, that's weird. Why'd she use Confuse Ray again? Silly Gen. 1 AI...

Yeah, at this point, I'm expecting to see all of the legendary birds. For Moltres, I guess I'll use Lord Helix, who should be highly resistant to anything Moltres can do. (I don't think Moltres can use Solarbeam in Gen. 1, and if it can, I'll have time to switch out before it hits.)
And Gary's final Pokémon is Vaporeon, which makes sense, since he started with a level 6 Eevee at the beginning of this hack (even though it looked like he chose Squirtle).
Hmm... I think Body Slam is my best move here. (Maybe I should've taught The Fonz Rock Slide or Ice Beam.)

I'm surprised I actually got enough Pokémon to qualify for the Exp. All during this Nuzlocke. Also, the two Pokémon I didn't even see were Mewtwo, and... Slowpoke, oddly enough. (I did the trainer-fly glitch in order to capture a level 7 Mew on Route 24, but I never actually used it.)
Hey, Lance. How's it going? Yeah, in Gen. 1 games, you can Surf and fish on these statues, which is weird. I guess they're coded to act like water for some reason.
Alright, one Lemonade will heal up that injury Radical has, and nobody else took any damage, so let's move on to the next opponent, Bruno!

Alright, I know Lorelei will likely be using ice-types, so I've switched Radical to the front here. He isn't weak to ice, and can strike those that are also part water-type super-effectively with Thunderbolt. (I'd use Battery Jay instead, but he is weak to ice, which could be a problem.)
Here we go!
TRIPLE FLAWLESS.
Fearow? Another normal/flying-type? Well, it does have a better flying-type attack with Drill Peck, but it's still not really an issue, especially if I switch to Battery Jay and Thunderbolt it!
